    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:287f223e-8ac3-4ce9-83f4-ff84c8095d14",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old woman of Mediterranean descent with a warm, expressive demeanor and a noticeably rushed energy about her. She is of average height and slightly overweight, with a body mass index hovering around 27. She presents to the clinic today dressed in business-casual attire, explaining she came straight from her office. She works as a marketing manager for a mid-sized tech firm, a role that demands long hours, frequent client lunches, and considerable deadline-related stress. She lives in a suburban home with her husband and two school-age children, and describes her lifestyle as \"constantly on the go.\"\n\n{patientName} reports a several-month history of a burning sensation that rises from her upper abdomen into her chest and throat, particularly after meals and when she lies down at night. She frequently wakes in the early hours of the morning with a sour or bitter taste in her mouth and a sensation of regurgitation. She notes that large, rich meals — a common occurrence at client dinners — reliably worsen her symptoms, as does her habit of having a glass of wine or two in the evenings to unwind.\n\nShe describes an intermittent dry, irritating cough that she initially attributed to seasonal allergies, and occasional hoarseness in the morning that typically resolves by mid-morning. She denies any dysphagia, odynophagia, involuntary weight loss, or frank haematemesis. She does admit to popping over-the-counter antacid tablets almost daily before her formal diagnosis was pursued.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys cooking (particularly spicy and tomato-based dishes), weekend hikes with her family, and binge-watching streaming series late into the night — a habit she acknowledges contributes to her lying down shortly after eating. She is a non-smoker but describes her coffee intake as \"probably too much,\" averaging three to four cups per day. She is socially active, maintains a close circle of friends, and reports moderate but chronic stress related to balancing her demanding career with family responsibilities.\n\n{patientName} is visibly fatigued during the consultation. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness on deep palpation but no guarding, rigidity, or organomegaly. Oropharyngeal inspection shows mild posterior pharyngeal erythema consistent with laryngopharyngeal reflux."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4d6b41cd-5a1c-41ae-b235-0fb3304da9fd",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
